AB  - Plant growth-promoting bacteria (PGPB) are typically soil bacteria that stimulate plant growth that can be used in a variety of ways when plant growth enhancements are required, often in association with plant roots, and sometimes on leaves or flowers, or within plant tissues. The most intensively studied use of PGPB has been in agriculture and horticulture where a number of PGPB formulations are currently available and are widely used as commercial products to enhance crop production, both under contained greenhouse as well as field conditions. In recent years, there has been only limited use of PGPB in forest regeneration, however there is increasing interest in using these bacteria in the phytoremediation of contaminated soils. Despite that, the use of genetically engineered PGPB under field conditions is currently extremely rare. As the biochemical and genetic mechanisms of plant growth promotion by these bacteria continue to be better understood, it is likely that this increasing understanding will translate into the development of more efficacious strains of PGPB.
